While I'm at it, here are a couple of other ideas on the clean energy
bandwagon.

One is chip-equipment maker Applied Materials (AMAT), which climbed more
than 4% one day last week after an analyst said the firm's solar power
equipment business could accelerate far faster than most believe.  No
surprise there.  But what caught my eye was the degree of acceleration. 
While management had projected that sales to solar companies would hit
$500 million in 2010, the broker estimated they'd hit $1.5 to $2 billion,
three to four times as high!  Applied Materials is a huge company, and its
chart is no better than tepid today, but it's good to see those
projections.

A more interesting play on clean energy is Zoltek (ZOLT) a company whose
low-cost carbon fiber is in high demand by makers of the blades of wind
turbines.  In the fourth quarter, Zoltek's revenue grew 95% to $30.3
million.  Equally important, analysts are expecting the company to have
positive earnings this year for the first time since 1998!  ZOLT's chart
is strong now.

Finally, there's Cameco (CCJ), the biggest supplier of the uranium used in
nuclear power plants.  Cameco has been growing revenues every year for the
past decade.  It's been profitable for every one of those years too, so
you know it's well managed.  And the stock, after spending eleven months
in a basing pattern, has just broken out to new highs on gargantuan
volume, a sign that big investors are getting back in.

