Finally, an Easter story, with a long preamble.

A few months ago I wrote a piece about our young Ukrainian friends.   
To recap: four years ago my wife and I hosted a 15-year-old girl from
Ukraine, Halyna, who spent four weeks at an American high school with our
daughter, and then returned to Ukraine.  In the years following that
visit, she moved on to the University at Kiev, transferred to the
University of Lethbridge in Alberta, Canada, and this year transferred to
Salem State College, where she's majoring in business administration.  Now
19, she's both smart and pretty and no doubt will succeed at whatever she
tries.

Halyna now lives in Salem with her fiancé, Andriy, who's also from the
same town in Ukraine.  And living with us now for two weeks is a new high
school girl, Nataliya, here for the same one-month exchange.

What all these people seek is a better life.  As they put it, "There are
no jobs in Ukraine."

Andriy's college degree, earned in Kiev, is in accounting.  But he's
making better money here working in the construction business.   
Andriy's mother, back in Ukraine, is an eye doctor.  Working for the
state, 35 hours a week, she earns 150 dollars per month.  Nataliya's
mother is a dental assistant, working in . . . Rome, Italy.  That's where
the money is.

Someday Ukraine will offer more opportunity, but progress happens slowly. 
Freed from the control of the Soviet Union just sixteen years ago, the
country lacks the entrepreneurial spirit that drives the world's
faster-growing economies.  It's still weighed down by a heavy bureaucracy.
 And its government is in turmoil; on April 3, President Yuschenko
(claiming deep corruption) signed a bill dissolving Parliament, but
Parliament declined to dissolve, and now the case will head to the Supreme
Court.

Anyway, I mentioned last week that our family would hide 14 dozen eggs for
assorted family and friends on Easter, and so we did.  But first we spent
hours on Saturday afternoon dying every single one.   
It's our tradition, and it's a lot of fun, especially when you have
artists in the family.

But knowing the old Ukrainian tradition of dying Easter eggs, I was
looking forward to Sunday, hoping to see some superior artisanry.  On that
big day, however, the Ukrainians first joined other friends at church, and
then went off to a full Ukrainian dinner.  So it wasn't until late in the
day that they returned to our house, bringing traditional Easter bread and
eggs decorated with black, red and gold designs.  For a split-second, my
hopes were fulfilled.  But then I noticed the designs were on pre-printed
shrink-wrap sleeves, just like most Americans buy.

Disappointed, yes.  Surprised, not really.  Traditions, like everything
else, are subject to the forces of change.  But now I find myself
wondering if those shrink-wrap designs were made in China, where low wages
and a thriving spirit of entrepreneurship make the manufacture of almost
anything not just possible but likely.

In fact, in Saturday's issue of Cabot Wealth Advisory, we'll take a look
at Communism and Capitalism in China, from an insider's perspective.

